<br>
If warriors complain about a lack of desirability in PoP then they're no better than rangers were in Kunark.   Be silent and hope VI will fix what's broken with the class.<br>
<br>
I would counter with:<br>
<br>
1. Rangers WERE broken in Kunark<br>
<br>
2. The &quot;one thing that's broken with the class, Taunt&quot; is EXACTLY what people are complaining about.   We're demonstrating it's impact in the current game in terms of mana spent, grouping dynamics, ancillary party member heals, etc.<br>
<br>
3. If you think that if you stay quiet long enough, hopefully people will recognize the problem on their own and fix it, then you have a *lot* to learn about life.   When my new car is not working properly, I take it to to the dealer and tell them about it.   If they deny that it's a problem, then I prove it to them, if they do nothing, then I get louder, pointing out relevant documentation, if that doesn't work, the final step is to go away from the parts department, into the sales showroom and ask somewhat loudly of the sales manager &quot;But didn't you tell me that this thing had a warranty?   I thought I was buying a mechanically sound car from you&quot;    Sales types don't like aggrivated customers implying in front of potential customers that the sales force is a bunch of liars, they ensure that my problems get fixed quite quickly.  I almost *always* get my problems fixed, and never by hoping that there will eventually be a recall, and staying a good little customer. <br>
<br>
4. If you think that by pretending that things are fine will prevent other potential group members from learning that taunt sucks (actually not taunt, but the generation of aggro) and that we represent a grave danger to their characters in experience groups in EQ, I will say, I want no part in your little charade.   People already know, they've known for some time, and it's disingenuous to pretend.<br>
<br>
<br>
